            <a:r>
              <a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/>
              <a:t>WorkbookLoader solves a problem naive CSV ingestion ignores: tabular data has structure. Plain CSV chunks produce 'APAC,1200000,0.15,7,controller_A' — data analysts then decode this. WorkbookLoader produces 'Region: APAC | Annual_Spend_USD: 1200000 | Reserve_Target_Pct: 0.15 | Risk_Score: 7 | Control_Owner: controller_A'. Now queries like 'regions with risk score above 5' have something to match. Header detection scores the first 8 rows — points for multiple non-empty cells, unique values, alphabetic content, and cell length. Highest score becomes the header. This handles real-world patterns like title rows, date rows, blank rows before actual headers. _normalize_headers() deduplicates and fills blanks with Excel-column notation.</a:t>
            </a:r>
          </a:p>
        </p:txBody>
